\textbf{Analysis of Scenario Requirements:}

The core challenge is reconciling three data sources with different update frequencies (SQL Server hourly, CSV at 6 PM, Dataverse every 4 hours with a 2-hour lag) and ensuring the 8 AM executive report contains complete, consistent previous-day data.

\textbf{Statement A --- FALSE:}
A fixed 7:15 PM single scheduled refresh does not guarantee that the CSV file has finished writing and is fully available, since the 6 PM update may still be processing. \textbf{Query Folding} is beneficial but applies only to sources that support it (e.g., relational databases), not to flat CSV files. Triggering all sources simultaneously ignores the documented timing misalignment and risks incomplete data in the final report.

\textbf{Statement B --- TRUE:}
This is the correct strategy. \textbf{Power Automate} can monitor the network share for CSV file availability and completeness, then call the \textbf{Power BI REST API} (specifically the \textit{Refresh Dataset} endpoint) to trigger the dataset refresh only after all sources are confirmed ready. This event-driven approach eliminates reliance on fixed-time scheduling, directly addresses the latency of the CSV and Dataverse sources, and guarantees the 8 AM report contains fully reconciled data. This is a well-documented and supported Power BI integration pattern.

\textbf{Statement C --- FALSE:}
While \textbf{Power Platform Dataflows} are a legitimate ETL and data preparation tool that can consolidate sources, the proposed schedule (dataflow at 9 PM, Power BI refresh at 10 PM) risks pushing completion too late relative to executive morning needs and adds a full extra hour of latency without necessity. More critically, this option does not address the validation of source readiness before triggering consolidation, meaning the Dataverse 2-hour lag could still cause the dataflow to capture stale Dataverse data if it runs before Dataverse has fully synced.

\textbf{Statement D --- FALSE:}
\textbf{DirectQuery} mode is not supported for CSV files in Power BI; CSV sources must always be imported. Mixing DirectQuery (SQL Server) with Import mode (Dataverse, CSV) creates a \textbf{composite model} with inconsistent refresh semantics that cannot reliably reconcile data timing differences across sources. \textbf{Row-Level Security (RLS)} manages user-level data access permissions, not data freshness or timing synchronization.

\textbf{Best Practice Rationale:}
For multi-source scenarios with variable latency, an \textit{event-driven refresh} pattern using \textbf{Power Automate} and the \textbf{Power BI REST API} is the recommended enterprise approach. It decouples refresh scheduling from fixed clock times and ensures all upstream sources are validated before the dataset is refreshed, which is critical for executive-level decision-making reports.

