\textbf{Statement 1 — Import Mode Advantages: TRUE}
\textbf{Import Mode} copies the 2.8 million rows into the Power BI dataset and stores them locally. After a daily refresh at 2:00 AM (matching the source update cycle), all subsequent user queries execute against the in-memory \textbf{VertiPaq} engine. This delivers the fastest query performance, requires zero network bandwidth during dashboard interactions, and fully satisfies the stated daily refresh requirement.

\textbf{Statement 2 — DirectQuery Trade-off: TRUE}
\textbf{DirectQuery} submits every user interaction as a native SQL query to the source database. With 2.8 million rows and limited bandwidth, this creates multiple problems: each dashboard filter, drill-down, or cross-filter interaction triggers a network round-trip, resulting in noticeable latency and bandwidth consumption during peak usage when many users interact simultaneously.

\textbf{Statement 3 — Live Connection Prerequisite Not Met: TRUE}
\textbf{Live Connection} requires either \textbf{SQL Server Analysis Services} (on-premises or Azure) or an existing \textbf{Power BI Premium} semantic model. The scenario explicitly states the organization lacks Premium infrastructure and describes a direct SQL Server connection. Live Connection is not a viable option without additional infrastructure investment.

\textbf{Statement 4 — Dual Mode Trade-off: PARTIALLY TRUE}
\textbf{Dual Mode} (Composite Models in Power BI) can optimize certain scenarios, but it adds complexity, requires careful design, and does not address the stated constraints better than pure Import Mode. Given the daily refresh cycle and 2.8 million row volume, Dual Mode provides no compelling advantage over standard Import Mode in this context.

\textbf{Correct Choice: A}
\textbf{Import Mode} is the best-practice answer for this scenario. It delivers optimal interactive performance through local in-memory storage, fully respects the limited bandwidth constraint by keeping all queries local, aligns perfectly with the daily 2:00 AM refresh cycle, and requires no additional infrastructure investment. This combination of fast performance, bandwidth efficiency, and simplicity makes Import Mode the correct choice for PL-300 exam purposes.

\textbf{Statement 1 -- TRUE:} With 847 million transaction records and a 2.4 GB storage limit, importing the entire fact table is infeasible. At typical VertiPaq compression ratios of 8:1 to 12:1, the raw data would exceed 20 GB before compression. Additionally, hourly full refreshes of this magnitude would create unacceptable refresh windows and disrupt user access. \textit{Storage constraints and refresh frequency drive mode selection away from pure Import.}

\textbf{Statement 2 -- FALSE:} Pure \textbf{DirectQuery} with 847 million rows and 312 concurrent users creates severe performance bottlenecks. Every user filter interaction generates a live SQL query to the data warehouse. Even with columnstore indexes, the cumulative concurrent query load makes sub-3-second 95th percentile performance highly unlikely. \textbf{DirectQuery} also lacks the in-memory caching that accelerates repeated queries. \textit{DirectQuery trades storage efficiency for increased source query pressure -- unsuitable as a sole strategy under high concurrency.}

\textbf{Statement 3 -- TRUE:} A \textbf{Composite Model} architecture provides the optimal solution: (1) The fact table uses \textbf{DirectQuery} mode, preserving real-time freshness within the 90-second latency requirement; (2) Pre-built \textbf{aggregation tables} (e.g., sales by category, region, and month) are stored in \textbf{Import mode}, consuming minimal storage while serving the majority of user queries from cache in under 1 second; (3) Dimension tables use \textbf{Dual mode}, enabling fast joins against both cached aggregations and live DirectQuery queries. This architecture satisfies storage limits, concurrency requirements, latency constraints, and query performance SLAs simultaneously.

\textbf{Why other options fail:}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Option A:} Pure DirectQuery fails under 312 concurrent users -- Statement 2 is demonstrably false.
\item \textbf{Option C:} Import mode violates the 2.4 GB constraint at 847 million rows; incremental refresh helps but cannot overcome the fundamental size mismatch.
\item \textbf{Option D:} Live Connection is read-only and forces all queries through the source model -- it does not support local aggregations or Composite Model routing, making it the worst option for high concurrency.
\end{itemize}

